{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3dbb2f29-cfae-4df5-bfa2-aec6c9234f30","content":"For a .NET Web API project, use the **`webapi`** template:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n```\n\n### Authentication options (`--auth`):\n\n| Option | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single Azure AD tenant |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multiple Azure AD tenants |\n| `Windows` | Windows/Negotiate authentication |\n\n### Example with auth:\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain mydomain.onmicrosoft.com\n```\n\nYou can also add **JWT Bearer** or **API Key** auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer`. Want me to scaffold a project with a specific auth setup?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"953dd5d5-b11e-4e0b-ad1c-789f05db291a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":268,"requestId":"A7C6:229C6C:1526693:17B1CE9:6A051DB2"},"id":"59fdc547-f779-4517-a54c-cd4bca3c4ed9","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:56:25.193Z","parentId":"a64bc847-5788-4b72-b176-7ac36225675e"}
